nt||lb|*BWhat call did Fred make?^^2S|
mb|2s|hs|ss|nt|Fred chose to jump shift to 2@S - a bid that would get the approval of most textbooks (where opener is generally expected to jump shift with 19 HCP). Despite what the textbooks say, in retrospect we think that 1@S would have a been a better call. An important lesson we learned from ^*BJoey Silver^*N reveals why: ^*BA jump shift is a statement, not a question^*N.|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt|What this means is that a jump shift is not simply an expression of high card strength - it should be based on a hand that can control the auction. Fred did not know where he was going with his hand. He simply had a lot of points. His choice of 2@S crowded the auction, making it impossible to discover a possible club fit on some layouts.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|Another problem with 2@S is that this call would normally suggest longer diamonds than spades (which turned out to be a serious problem on the actual deal). A 1@S rebid is not without risk as 1@S is non-forcing. However, it would be very rare for Brad to pass 1@S here (especially given the partnership bidding style where all balanced hands rebid in notrump).|
